\par <h> <#/>WAYS OF ADMINISTRATION </h>
\par <#/>Drugs enter the blood stream through several routes. <#/>The following are the major ones:
\par <#/>1. Oral or through the mouth: These drugs are ingested and take some time to act.
\par <#/>2. Injections through muscles or straight to the veins: The effect is felt in seconds or minutes after administration.
\par <#/>3. Topical: This route is simplest and safest. <#/>It is just applied on the skin or part of the skin needing treatment. <#/>They take longer to act (days or weeks).
\par <#/>4. Inhalation: Some drugs are inhaled through the respiratory tract and the effect is as sudden as that one of injecting through the vein. <#/>Such drugs are like volatile gases, cigarette smoke, chemicals, for example petrol and glue.
\par <#/>5. Rectally or vaginally: Suppositories are inserted rectally while pessaries are inserted through the vagina but these are rare cases.
\par <h> <#/>EFFECTS OF DRUGS IN OUR BODIES </h>
\par <#/>When we take drugs, some physiological or pharmacological effects occur (immediate or acute effects). <#/>When a drug enters the blood stream, it reacts with our body cells. <#/>Either the cells are stimulated to act or they are blocked from acting. <
#/>Their function is changed and this influences our feelings, emotions and behaviour.
\par <h> <#/>USE OF DRUGS </h>
