\par }\pard\plain \qj\nowidctlpar\widctlpar\adjustright \f56\fs20 {<#/>}{\f0\fs24\lang2057 Abstract \emdash  Studies were commenced to collect and identify the phlebotomine sandflies found in Na
irobi. <#/>These studies were also aimed at determining their numbers as well as assessing the effects of seasonal changes on the sandfly population. <#/>Four trapping methods, namely, light traps, sticky traps, aspiration and human bait were employed. <#
/>Eight species and one undescribed species were recorded over a period of 6 months. <#/>The identified species included }{\i\f0\fs24\lang2057 Phlebotomus guggisbergi }{\f0\fs24\lang2057 (Kirk and Lewis), }{\i\f0\fs24\lang2057 P}{\f0\fs24\lang2057 . }{
\i\f0\fs24\lang2057 rodhaini }{\f0\fs24\lang2057 (Parrot), }{\i\f0\fs24\lang2057 Sergentomyia adleri }{\f0\fs24\lang2057 (Theodor), }{\i\f0\fs24\lang2057 S}{\f0\fs24\lang2057 . }{\i\f0\fs24\lang2057 harveyi }{\f0\fs24\lang2057 
(Heisch, Guggisberg and Teesdale) and }{\i\f0\fs24\lang2057 S}{\f0\fs24\lang2057 . }{\i\f0\fs24\lang2057 bedfordi }{\f0\fs24\lang2057 
(Newstead) and an undescribed species. <#/>Most of the sandfly species trapped showed seasonal prevalence. <#/>The seasonal variation was closely related to the weather conditions. <#/>Sandflies were found in termite mounds, animal burr
ows, caves and dugouts some of which were near human habitations. <#/>Termite mounds and animal burrows were the most preferred habitats.
\par <h> <#/>}{\b\f0\fs24\lang2057 INTRODUCTION}{\f0\fs24\lang2057  </h>
\par <#/>Sandflies are haematophagus insects which makes them important medical vectors. <#/>Species of the genera }{\i\f0\fs24\lang2057 Phlehotomus }{\f0\fs24\lang2057 and }{\i\f0\fs24\lang2057 Sergentomyia }{\f0\fs24\lang2057 
are restricted to the old world, being common in Africa, the Indian subregion and Central Asia. <#/>}{\i\f0\fs24\lang2057 Lutzomyia }{\f0\fs24\lang2057 species occur in the new world, especially in the forested areas of Central and Southern America.

\par <#/>Sandflies are known vectors of leishmaniasis caused by different species of the genus }{\i\f0\fs24\lang2057 Leishmania. <#/>}{\f0\fs24\lang2057 There are over 20 known species of }{\i\f0\fs24\lang2057 Leishmania }{\f0\fs24\lang2057 of which over
 a dozen are associated with various forms of leishmaniasis }{\v\f0\fs24\lang2057 (Peters and Killick-Kendrick, 1987)}{\f0\fs24\lang2057 . 
