\f0\fs24\lang2057 <#/>Sandflies show seasonal prevalence and in most cases exhibit a more or less marked seasonal variation in numbers }{\v\f0\fs24\lang2057 (Kirk and Lewis, 1940; Martin, 1938; Wanson, 1942; Adler and Theodor, 1931). }{\f0\fs24\lang2057 
<#/>The objectives of this study were firstly to identify the phlebotomine sandflies found in Nairobi. <#/>Secondly
, to assess their abundance and relate the effects of seasonal changes on sandfly population, and thirdly to determine if sandfly species existing in the Nairobi area may be potential vectors of leishmaniasis. <#/>Nairobi is closely situated to the Athi R
iver Plain foci of visceral leishmaniasis.
\par <h> <#/>}{\b\f0\fs24\lang2057 MATERIAL AND METHODS </h>
\par <h> <#/>}{\i\f0\fs24\lang2057 Study sites}{\f0\fs24\lang2057  </h>
\par <#/>Three study sites namely, Langata, Kibera and Roysambu in the Nairobi area were selected. <#/>The sites were identified through a preliminary survey to
 determine areas where sandflies were abundant and where there were reports by inhabitants of bites by flies other than mosquitoes.
\par <h> <#/>}{\i\f0\fs24\lang2057 Trapping methods}{\f0\fs24\lang2057  </h>
\par <#/>}{\i\f0\fs24\lang2057 The sticky trap method. <#/>}{\f0\fs24\lang2057 Castor oil traps adapted from the devices used by Petrisheva (1935) and Blasova (1932) both cited by Kirk and Lewis (1940) were used. <#/>Transparent polythene sheets
\par <#/>1 x 1 m and 0.25 mm thick devised by Mutinga (1981), were coated with castor oil on b
oth surfaces and fixed near resting sites of sandflies as described by Mutinga (1981). <#/>These sheets were held by strings in and outside houses, in the forest near tree trunks, caves and near termite mounds.
\par <#/>The sandflies were expected to be trapped
 as they flew in and out of their habitats or as they came into houses to feed. <#/>Similar sheets measuring 20 x 30 cm were also used. <#/>These sheets were fixed on forked sticks and inserted into small animal burrows on cracks in the ground. <#/>The sh
e
ets were also rolled and placed in the ventilation shafts of termite mounds and sandflies were trapped as they hopped in and out of the shafts. <#/>A total of 30 traps were placed at the sites in the evening at 1830 hr and removed in the morning at 0700 h
r
, three nights a week for a period of 6 months (November 1989 to April 1990). <#/>The trapped sandflies were then picked from the transparent sheets since they were easily distinguished from other dipterans. <#/>A fine camel hair brush (No. 2) was used to
 remove the sandflies from the sheet. <#/>The sandflies were then placed in specimen tubes which were well labelled and contained detergent saline.
